Durban - Three people have been killed in a freak thunderstorm that hit two KwaZulu-Natal wards this week. In the first incident, a 13-year-old boy was killed after he was struck by lightening while walking back from school. According to KwaZulu-Natal spokesperson for Cooperative Governance and Traditional Affairs, Senzo Mzila, the youngster attended Mampunga Primary School in Mtubatuba in Ward 17. He said in the second instance, a 42-year-old mother and her child were fatally injured when the walls of their home caved in on them in Nkwalini in theÂ uThungulu District Municipality. Cogta KZN MEC Sipho Hlomuka has extended his condolences to the families. "Disaster teams have been dispatched to provide support to the two families," he said. Hlomuka has also warned residents to continue to exercise great caution as inclement weather conditions continue to pose a serious risk to human life in the province. On Thursday evening, residents living in and around parts of Pietermaritzburg were left without electricity following a freak storm. Cogta teams will be on standby in the event that the weather patterns change. Earlier in the day, the South African Weather Services issued a warning about a storm that was seen travelling towards PMB.         The Mercury